ilable through Luminos, University of California Press's Open Access publishing program. Visit www.luminosoa.org to learn more. This exciting volume presents the work and research of the Rivers of the Anthropocene Network, an international collaborative group of scientists, social scientists, humanists, artists, policy makers, and community organizers working to produce innovative transdisciplinary research on global freshwater systems. In an attempt to bridge disciplinary divides, the essays in this volume address the challenge in studying the intersection of biophysical and human sociocultural systems in the age of the Anthropocene, a new geological epoch of humans' own making. Featuring contributions from authors in a rich diversity of disciplines-from toxicology to archaeology to philosophy-this book is an excellent resource for students and scholars studying both freshwater systems and the Anthropocene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh  aagency.  aanthropocene.  ablue nile basin.  acase study.  achicago river.  acity state.  adrainage.  aecological.  aecology.  aecosystem.  aengineering.  aethics.  aethnography.  aflooding.  agreat flood.  aimmigration.  alandscape.  anatural history.  anatural world.  anile river.  apublic ecology.  arivers.  ariverscape.  ascholars.  aseine river.  asociety.  awater system.  awaterways.  awestern europe.  aworld history.1 aBenjamin, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo